INTERPRETATION #1 of Pre-QC: Here, in this location of your analyses, please insert a description of the interpretation you draw regarding your plots. You must note anything important about the figure you’ve created about your data including any spikes in quality and also the general trend of the raw QC plots.

These plots showing the pre-QC quality scores of the raw sequencing data for the project, which aggregate 29 sequencing files, and were generated with 2x300 bp sequencing on an Illumina MiSeq Sequencer:

  1. Early Bases Have a Drop in Quality (~Cycle 0-10) Both forward and reverse reads show a slight drop in quality at the beginning (~Cycle 0-10). However, this drop remains mostly above Q30, which is acceptable. In this case, I will use the ‘trimLeft’ parameter to trim the primers in both forward and reverse reads.

  2. High Quality in Mid-Read (~Cycle 10-210) The sequencing quality is stable and above ~25-30 across most of the sequencing cycle/read (Cycle 10-300). This suggests that most of the read length is high-quality and can be retained.

  3. Decline in Reverse Reads After ~210 Cycles The reverse reads exhibit a notable drop in quality after ~210 cycles, dropping below Q25. The decline is more severe in reverse reads than in forward reads, indicating a high sequencing error rate. This suggests that truncating the reverse reads around Cycle ~200-220 might improve quality. Therefore, I will truncate the read using ‘truncLen = 210’ to remove those final 90 poor-quality bases at the end of the read.

  4. Forward Reads Maintain Quality Slightly Longer (~Cycle 230-300) The forward reads show a more gradual decline in quality after Cycle 230, but they remain above ~25-30 longer than the reverse reads. The final cycles (~280-300) show a steep drop in quality, which is common for Illumina sequencing. This suggests that truncating forward reads around Cycle ~280 to remove poor-quality bases. Therefore, I will truncate the read using ‘trunclen = 280’ to remove those final 20 poor-quality bases at the end of the read.

Filter and Trim Reads

# Assign and write out filtered fastq files 
# Therefore, we do not need to trim the primers, because they were not sequenced
filtered_reads <- 
  filterAndTrim(fwd = forward_reads, filt = filtered_forward_reads,
              rev = reverse_reads, filt.rev = filtered_reverse_reads,
              maxN = 0,
              # The sequence quality is not bad, so I choose to use maxEE = c(2,2)
              maxEE = c(2,2), 
              # Trim the primers sequences in the forward and reverse reads
              trimLeft = c(16, 20),
              # Trim final 20 bases in the forward & trim final 90 bases in the reverse read
              truncLen = c(280, 210), 
              truncQ = 2, rm.phix = TRUE, compress = TRUE, multithread = TRUE)

The plots above show the post-QC quality scores of the sequencing data after applying quality filtering and trimming. Quality filtering successfully removed poor-quality reads and trimmed low-quality tails, leading to improved overall read quality. 1. Forward Reads Post-QC The forward reads maintain high quality (Q30+) throughout most of the read length. A slight decline in quality is visible after ~230 cycles, but still largely above a Phred of 30. 2. Reverse Reads Post-QC Initial bases (~0-10 cycles) remain stable, suggesting that any low-quality bases were effectively trimmed. The mid-read section (~10-170 cycles) maintains strong Q30+ quality with minimal degradation. A quality drop-off is still visible after ~170 cycles, but it is much less severe than before, meaning the QC process effectively removed the worst low-quality regions while preserving usable data.

Read Retention Post-QC

# Make output into dataframe 
filtered_df <- as.data.frame(filtered_reads) %>%
  mutate(percent.retained = reads.out/reads.in)

# Intuition check
# Visualize it in table format 
DT::datatable(filtered_df)
# Let's calculate some statistics
read_stats_df <- 
  filtered_df %>%
  reframe(median_reads_in = median(reads.in),
          median_reads_out = median(reads.out),
          median_percent_retained = (median(reads.out)/median(reads.in)),
          max_percent_retained = max(reads.out/reads.in),
          min_percent_retained = min(reads.out/reads.in))

# Take a look at it!
read_stats_df
##   median_reads_in median_reads_out median_percent_retained max_percent_retained
## 1           45573            41736               0.9158054            0.9265737
##   min_percent_retained
## 1            0.7743625
# Plot it 
numSeqs_QC_dotplot <-
  filtered_df %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = reads.in, y = reads.out)) + 
  geom_point(alpha = 0.5, size = 2) + 
  labs(x = "# of Raw Seqs", 
       y = "# of Seqs Retained") + 
  # Now let's add a 1:1 line for reference of keeping 100% of the reads
  geom_abline(slope=1, intercept = 0, color = "deeppink")

# Now, let's look at the number of reads retained in a histogram
numRetained_QC_histplot <- 
  filtered_df %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = reads.out)) + 
  geom_histogram() + 
  labs(x = "# of Seqs Retained", 
       y = "# of Samples") 

# Create a histogram of percent reads retained in a histogram
percSeqs_QC_histplot <- 
  filtered_df %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = percent.retained)) + 
  geom_histogram() + 
  labs(x = "% of Seqs Retained", 
       y = "# of Samples") + 
  # Set the scale to be between 0-1 (0-100%)
  scale_x_continuous(limits = c(0, 1))

# Now, let's put the plots together
numSeqs_QC_dotplot + numRetained_QC_histplot + percSeqs_QC_histplot + 
  plot_annotation(tag_levels = 'A')

This figure presents three panels showing how many sequences were retained after quality filtering and trimming in the DADA2 pipeline.

Panel A: Scatter Plot of Raw vs. Retained Sequences • X-axis: Number of raw sequences before filtering. • Y-axis: Number of sequences retained after filtering. • Pink Line: The diagonal line represents perfect retention (i.e., no sequences lost). Interpretation of Panel A: Most points are close to the diagonal, suggesting good read retention across samples. Some points fall below the diagonal, indicating that a few samples lost a moderate number of reads. No extreme outliers, meaning no sample was unexpectedly depleted. Overall: The filtering step was effective while preserving most sequences, ensuring sufficient data retention.

Panel B: Histogram of the Number of Sequences Retained per Sample • X-axis: Number of sequences retained per sample. • Y-axis: Number of samples with that many retained sequences. Interpretation of Panel B: Most samples retained between ~35,000 and 42,000 or between ~44,000 and 53,000 sequences, indicating that the majority of data was preserved. A small number of samples have lower retention, but there is no drastic loss. Overall: The filtering process successfully retained a consistent number of reads across most samples.

Panel C: Histogram of Percent of Sequences Retained • X-axis: Proportion (%) of sequences retained per sample. • Y-axis: Number of samples at each proportion. Interpretation of Panel C. The majority of samples retained 75–95% of their reads, indicating successful quality filtering. Median retention is ~93% (good); Max retention: ~95% (great); Min retention: 75% (good).
